<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
No habitat data were reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, WJ" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" publicationUrl="10.4039/Ent639-1" refId="B2" refString="Brown, WJ, 1931. Revision of the North American Aegialiinae (Coleoptera). The Canadian Entomologist 63, 10.4039/Ent639-1" title="Revision of the North American Aegialiinae (Coleoptera)" url="10.4039/Ent639-1" volume="63" year="1931">Brown (1931)</bibRefCitation>
or 
<bibRefCitation author="Gordon, RD" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 37" refId="B5" refString="Gordon, RD, Cartwright, OL, 1988. North American representatives of the tribe Aegialiini (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Aphodiinae). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 461: 1 - 37" title="North American representatives of the tribe Aegialiini (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Aphodiinae)" volume="461" year="1988">Gordon and Cartwright (1988)</bibRefCitation>
for this species. The 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Aegialia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Aegialia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(sensu stricto) are usually found on coastal and inland dune systems or on gravel shores of streams and ponds (subgenus 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Psammoporus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Psammoporus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Gordon, RD" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 37" refId="B5" refString="Gordon, RD, Cartwright, OL, 1988. North American representatives of the tribe Aegialiini (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Aphodiinae). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 461: 1 - 37" title="North American representatives of the tribe Aegialiini (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Aphodiinae)" volume="461" year="1988">Gordon and Cartwright 1988</bibRefCitation>
). The adults from New Brunswick were found under driftwood on a sand dune along a sea beach. Adults were collected during late May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
